I noticed in the graphical analysis that the explanatory variables “surf” and “strat” had not statistically significant relationship with the target variable “point”(See the rightmost column in the matrix plot).The absolute correlation (Corr.) values were small (< 0.2) and the p-value that indicates statistic significance, should be p < 0.05. In the plots and the model summaries the significance level is portrayed with asterisks (*). I confirmed this with creating a regression model with multiple explanatory values and inspecting the statistical significance from the summary, revealing the same result; explanatory variables “surf” and “strat” had no statistically significant relationship with the target variable “point” regarding the intercept and the slope or beta-parameter (attitude in summary table).

Thus I removed these from the model fit, and run the model fit again with a single as follows in this R code chunk were also the summary for the model fit:

my_model <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = lrn2014)

In this case with a single explanatory variable “attitude”, the summary above reveals that a statistically significant relationship exists between the explanatory and the target variables. for both the slope and the intercept.

R-squared should accurately reflect the percentage of the dependent variable variation

Finally in this R code chunk the diagnostic plots Residual vs. Fitted values, Normal QQ-plot and Residual vs. Leverage are plotted:

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(my_model, which = c(1,2,5))

From these three figures one can interpret following:

The residuals vs. model values scatter plot (top left plot in the figure above) is a tool for assessing the constant variance assumption. According to the constant variance assumption the size of the model errors should not depend on the explanatory variables. There are is not a clear pattern or dependency between model fitted values and residuals that would indicate problems with the constant variance assumption.

QQ-plot (top right plot in figure above) is a tool to analyze the normality assumption i.e. that the errors of the model are normally distributed. The points plotted, follow the line with some deviation at top and bottom values, errors may be considered as reasonably normally distributed

Leverage measures how much impact a single observation has on the model. Residuals vs. leverage plot (bottom left plot in figure above) is a tool for identifying which observations have unusually high impact. The Residuals vs. leverage plot reveals that there are no observations that have unusual impact on the model. Notice the small values on the x-axis (Leverage).

#Import libraries

The dataset used in this exercise is available online: http://s3.amazonaws.com/assets.datacamp.com/production/course_2218/datasets/alc.txt

The dataset processed in this exercise is a combination of two original datasets on performance in two distinct subjects: Mathematics (mat) and Portuguese language (por).

The combined dataset used contains 35 variables (columns) and 382 observations (rows). The description of the variables and more detailed description of the dataset can be found here

The first step is to download the data (this is already the combined dataset).

#Download data, with a comma separator between columns:
alc <- read.table("http://s3.amazonaws.com/assets.datacamp.com/production/course_2218/datasets/alc.txt",

As the purpose of this analysis is to study the relationships between high/low alcohol consumption and some of the other variables in the data. i choose following 4 variables for the analysis: 

freetime - free time after school (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high) 
goout - going out with friends (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high) 
health - current health status (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - very good) 
absences - number of school absences (numeric: from 0 to 93) 

My personal hypothesis for the relationships of the chosen variables with alcohol consumption are 
freetime - Alcohol consumption increases with increased freetime  goout - Alcohol consumption increases the more students go out with friends 
health - Alcohol consumption increases with decreased health status 
absences - Alcohol consumption increases with increased school absences 

Next the distributions of the variables are explored graphically and numerically: 

For simplicity a new dataset is defined with the 4 variables, the gender variable and alcohol use:

#Acquire the variables from the original dataset 
sex <- alc$sex
freetime <- alc$freetime
goout <- alc$goout
health <- alc$health
absences <- alc$absences
alc_use <- alc$alc_use
high_use <- alc$high_use

alc2 <- data.frame(sex = sex, freetime = freetime, goout = goout, health = health,
                   absences = absences, alc_use = alc_use, high_use = high_use)

Here we inspect the relationships between the variables graphically (and numerically) with this type of summarizing matrix plot.

p <- ggpairs(alc2, mapping = aes(col = sex, alpha = 0.3), lower = list(combo = wrap("facethist", bins = 20)))
p

The distributions are inspected graphically more closely with bar plots:

#Draw bar plots of the distributions of the chosen variables 
gather(alc2) %>% ggplot(aes(value))  + geom_bar() + facet_wrap("key", scales = "free")

The exploration (The first matrix plot) of the variables revealed that there are statistically significant relationships (p < 0.05) between alcohol consumption (“alc_use”) and the variables freetime, goout and absences. There is no statistically significant relationship between alcohol consumption and student health. The strongest correlation can be found between gouout and alcohol consumption. 

Compared to the hypotheses stated earlier the relationships were not as strong as I thought. There was however a predicted relationship between alcohol consumption and every other variable, but student health. Seems like alcohol consumption does not affect the health at younger ages… 

Regarding the distributions (graphically interpretation) of the variables, goout and freetime are somewhat normally distributed. While absences, health and alc_use have half-normal or gamma distributions.

Now logistic regression is used to statistically explore the relationship between the chosen variables and the binary high/low alcohol consumption as the target variable.

#find the model with glm()
m <- glm(high_use ~ freetime + goout + health + absences + sex, data = alc2, family = "binomial")

#print out the summary of the model 
summary(m)

I did not really grasp how to interpret the summary of the logistic regression model (m) with categorical values. Other than that there is a statistically strong relationship between heavy use of alcohol (“high_use”) and the variables goout, absences and sexM.

Interpretation of the coefficients of the model as odds ratios indicate that increased outgoing (goout) is twice (2 times) as likely to increase alcohol consumption than decreased going out. Similarly, male (sexM) students are twice as likely to be high users compared to female students.The other variables do not have a relationship with high consumption of alcohol (“high_use”).These results are in contradiction to the hypotheses presented in the beginning of this exercise.

Next the variables that had a significant relationship i.e. goout, absences and sex will be used to explore the predictive power of the model:

# A model with the variables with an existing significant realtionship are used 
m =  glm(high_use ~  goout + absences + sex, data = alc2, family = "binomial")

# Use the model (m) to predict() the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(m, type = "response")

# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc2'
alc2 <- mutate(alc2, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
alc2 <- mutate(alc2, prediction = probabilities >0.5)

# Finally, tabulate the target variable versus the predictions
table(high_use = alc2$high_use, prediction = alc2$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   255   15
##    TRUE     66   46
# Plot the results 
g <- ggplot(alc2, aes(x = probability, y = high_use, col = prediction))
g + geom_point()

# define a loss function (total prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  sum(n_wrong)
}
 #call loss_func to compute the total number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class = alc2$high_use, prob = alc2$probability)
## [1] 81

From the 2X2 Cross tabulation one can interpret that the non-high (FLASE) alcohol consumption was predicted by the model correctly for 255 students. High alcohol consumption (TRUE) was predicted correctly for 46 students.

The loss function indicates that 81 predictions of 382 are wrong. The same result can be interpreted from the 2X2 Cross tabulation as the wrong predictions 66 + 15 = 81. I am not familiar with guessing strategies, but compared to a yes,no,yes,no,yes,no etc. guessing strategy the model m is more accurate.

Here a 10-fold cross validation is performed on the model:

# define a loss function (average prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

  # compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class = alc2$high_use, prob = alc2$probability)
## [1] 0.2120419
# 10-fold cross-validation
library(boot)
cv <- cv.glm(data = alc2, cost = loss_func, glmfit = m, 10)


# display average number of wrong predictions in the cross validation
cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2015707

The average number of wrong predictions obtained with the cross validation for the introduced model m. is 0.204. It is somewhat smaller than the value introduced to the model introduced in DataCamp, which had about 0.26 error.

The dataset “Boston” is on housing values in the suburbs of Boston.

The data has the following columns: crim -per capita crime rate by town.
zn - proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
indus - proportion of non-retail business acres per town.
chas - Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise).
nox - nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million).
rm - average number of rooms per dwelling.
age - proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940.
dis - weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres.
rad - index of accessibility to radial highways.
tax - full-value property-tax rate per $10,000.
ptratio - pupil-teacher ratio by town.
black - 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town.
lstat - lower status of the population (percent).
medv - median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s.

The source for the data:

Harrison, D. and Rubinfeld, D.L. (1978) Hedonic prices and the demand for clean air. J. Environ. Economics and Management 5, 81–102.

Belsley D.A., Kuh, E. and Welsch, R.E. (1980) Regression Diagnostics. Identifying Influential Data and Sources of Collinearity. New York: Wiley.

Graphical overview of the distributions of the variables and relationships between the variables

p <- ggpairs(Boston, mapping = aes(alpha = 0.3), lower = list(combo = wrap("facethist", bins = 20)))
p

From the data we can interpret visually that the data has distributions:
crim - exponential distribution
zn - exponential distribution
indus - bi-modal distribution
chas - exponential distribution
nox -triangluar distribution rm - normal distribution
age - exponential distribution
dis - triangular distribution
rad - bi-modal distribution
tax - bi-modal distribution
ptratio - triangular distribution
black - exponential distribution
lstat - triangular distribution
medv - almost normal distribution or triangular distribution

The relationships between the variables (Corr = Correlations) can be interpreted from the matrix plot.

4. Standardizing the dataset and create categorial variable of the crime rate

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crim)


# Finally, plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1.5)

Now run the K-means algorithm on the dataset

#Run k-means algorithm on the dataset
km <-kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 3)
pairs(Boston[6:10], col = km$cluster)

Now let’s investigate what is the optimal number of clusters and run the k-means algorithm again and then visualize the result.

When one plots the number of clusters and the total WCSS, the optimal number of clusters is when the total WCSS drops radically.

#K-means might produce different results every time, because it randomly assigns the initial cluster centers. The function set.seed() can be used to deal with that.
set.seed(123)
# determine the number of clusters
k_max <- 10

# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(boston_scaled, k)$tot.withinss})

# visualize the results
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

In the figure above we can see that WCSS drops radically at 2, thus the optimal number of clusters is 2. Now let’s plot the figure to visualize the results

# k-means clustering
km <-kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 2)

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(boston_scaled, col = km$cluster)
